{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180807110712|853854466","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Rick_W._Allen","to":"Rick W. Allen"}],"pages":{"44305318":{"pageid":44305318,"ns":0,"title":"Rick W. Allen","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-11T15:43:41Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Rick Allen\n|image       = Rick Allen Official Photo, 114th Congress.jpg\n|state       = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|district    = {{ushr|GA|12|12th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[John Barrow (U.S. politician)|John Barrow]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1951|11|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Augusta, Georgia|Augusta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education   = [[Auburn University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n|website     = {{url|allen.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Richard Wayne Allen''' (born November 7, 1951) is an American politician who serves [[Georgia's 12th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014]]. He took office on January 3, 2015.\n\n==Career==\nAllen attended [[Auburn University]] and earned a degree in building construction. He is the founder of R.W. Allen and Associates, a construction company headquartered in Augusta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/136062/rick-allen#.VFlwdfTF_Zk|title=Project Vote Smart \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2012}}\nAllen ran in the Republican primary for the 12th district against three other candidates. Allen advanced to the runoff, but lost to State Representative [[Lee Anderson (politician)|Lee Anderson]], 49.7% to 50.3%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/news/government/elections/2012-09-05/vote-recount-certifies-lee-anderson-winner-gop-runoff-us|title=The Augusta Chronicle: Local & World News, Sports & Entertainment in Augusta, GA|website=The Augusta Chronicle|language=en|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref> Anderson went on to lose the general election to incumbent John Barrow.\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2014}}\nAllen ran again in 2014, this time making it to the general election. Allen defeated Barrow in the November election, in a result considered an upset even though the 12th had been made significantly more Republican in redistricting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2014/11/04/tonights-rolling-blog-cnn-exit-polls-put-georgia-u-s-senate-race-at-49-48/|title=Nunn, Carter, and Barrow defeated; Georgia\u2019s Democratic revolution is stillborn \u2013 Political Insider blog|publisher=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/state-regional-govt-politics/rick-allen-upsets-john-barrow-for-georgia/nhzbx/|title=Rick Allen upsets John Barrow for Georgia congressional seat|publisher=Ajc.com|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation and Forestry]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nDuring a closed-door Republican meeting discussing an amendment that prohibited discrimination against [[LGBT]] workers, Allen read a [[Bible]] verse that says about homosexuals \"they which commit such things are worthy of death.\"  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3612827/It-f-king-ridiculous-GOP-lawmakers-ditch-meeting-representative-tries-shame-Bible-passage-homosexuality.html|title='It was f**king ridiculous': Some GOP lawmakers ditch meeting after representative tries to shame them with Bible passage on homosexuality that calls gays 'reprobate' and 'worthy of death'|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/16/us/after-orlando-a-political-divide-on-gay-rights-still-stands.html|title=After Orlando, a Political Divide on Gay Rights Still Stands|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>  Allen told the assembled Republicans that they are \"going to Hell\" if they vote for the proposed anti-discrimination amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/davidbadash/gop_congressman_quotes_bible_tells_republicans_they_are_going_to_hell_if_they_vote_for_lgbt_bill|title=GOP Congressman Quotes Bible, Tells Republicans They Are 'Going to Hell' if They Vote for LGBT Bill|publisher=[[The New Civil Rights Movement]]|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n \nAfter dozens were killed at a gay nightclub in Orlando, Florida, Allen offered prayers to the family of the victims but refused to apologize or retract his past comments stating that homosexuals were \"worthy of death.\"  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/policy/congressman-read-anti-gay-bible-verse-prays-orlando-victims|title=Congressman Who Read Anti-Gay Bible Verse Prays for Orlando Victims' Loved Ones|publisher=[[Roll Call]]|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/16/us/after-orlando-a-political-divide-on-gay-rights-still-stands.html|title=After Orlando, a Political Divide on Gay Rights Still Stands|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=16 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAllen lives in [[Augusta, Georgia]]. A [[Methodist]], he is married to Robin Allen and has four children.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Auburn University people]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n* [https://allen.house.gov/ Congressman Rick Allen] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.rickwallen.com/ Rick Allen for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Rick_Allen_%5BR-12%5D|Rick Allen}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rickallen03}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=A000372 | votesmart=136062 | fec=H2GA12121 | congress=rick-allen/2239 }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Georgia\n| district=1\n| before=[[John Barrow (U.S. politician)|John Barrow]]\n| start=2015\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pete Aguilar]]<br>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=314th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brian Babin]]<br>R-[[Texas]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{GA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Rick}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Augusta, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:American construction businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Auburn University alumni]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]"}]}}}}